				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Alright - so here's a follow up question on this...<br /><br />I have understood the very easy method of implementing 16bit math to handle 'sub pixel movement'/acceleration...however I'm sort of confused how to translate that to screen position.  For acceleration, for instance...it was very simple to add a low bit that sort of acts as a 'counter' so to speak, which allows me to control the rate at which things accelerate/decelerate.  No problem.  When the low bit is increased passed 255 it carries to the high bit, and then that high bit can be added to the position.  Meaning I can slow it down to 1/255 of a frame.<br /><br />However...I guess what I'm confused about - let's pretend 1 pixel per frame is too fast.  Let's pretend I have my player moving at quarter of a pixel per frame.  So the low bit would be increasing by 64 each frame.  If I'm adding the high bit to the player's position in order to establish his movement, that would mean that he would not move for the first three frames.<br /><br />I found this a problem when working with acceleration.  I'd accelerate very slowly (adding just 1 to the low bit that represented player's speed so I could see if it was working), and then used math with the high bit to establish the player's new position.  Of course, this meant that for the first 255 frames, there was no movement at all, as the high bit was zero.  Then, it moved at a speed of one pixel for frame for the next 255 frames, then it moved at a speed of 2 pixels per frame for the next 255 frames...and so on.<br /><br />I guess the question is - is it possible to represent the position in sub-pixels?  Some sort of correlation to that low bit so that movement/acceleration looks smoother at any speed?<br /><br />This may be a simple question (maybe even as simple as the 16bit math to generate sub pixel movement!), but I can't quite figure it out.<br /><br />Thanks!</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
