				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The answer is you do exactly what you did before. You write the simple variable playerX to spriteRAM+whatever. Subpixel position doesn't affect on screen position at all. <br /><br />I guess, here's what it used to look like:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">lda #$01<br />sta playerspeed<br /><br />;Later<br /><br />lda playerX<br />clc<br />adc playerspeed<br />sta playerX<br /><br />;Even later<br /><br />lda playerX<br />sta spriteRAM,x<br /></div><br />Here's what it'd look like with subpixels.<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">lda #$00<br />sta playerspeedlow<br /><br />lda #$01<br />sta playerspeedhigh<br />;This is the exact same speed as before.<br />;The high byte represents pixels, the low byte represents sub pixels.<br />;If you wanted to move less than 1 pixel a frame, the high byte would be zero<br /><br />;Later<br /><br />lda playerXsubpixel<br />clc<br />adc playerspeedlow<br />sta playerXsubpixel<br /><br />lda playerX<br />adc playerspeedhigh<br />sta playerX<br /><br />;Even later<br /><br />lda playerX;This is the same.<br />sta spriteRAM,x<br /></div><br />If you really, really, really want subpixels to affect display, well... I covered that in the PM. But I honestly wouldn't bother with it. Super Mario Bros has no effect when Mario is walking. At max walking speed, sometimes he moves one pixel, sometimes he moves 2. It still looks fine and smooth even without an effect. If speeds lower than 1 pixel are what you're worried about, keep in mind that most of the fastest animation runs at less than half the framerate speed of video games and people still realize it's moving.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
